{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614508"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:47:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:47:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16372"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74658"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7106"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21552"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74658"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old female presented with intermittent headaches and urinary incontinence. Her family members also noticed her to be unsteady on her feet and confused. CT brain demonstrated tetraventricular hydrocephalus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location of the fourth ventricle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Between the thalamus and hypothalamus","Between the pons and medulla anteriorly, and cerebellum posteriorly","Between the third ventricle and cerebral aqueduct","Between the cerebral hemispheres in the midline","Within each cerebral hemisphere"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fourth ventricle is a crucial component of the ventricular system of the brain. \u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the pons and medulla anteriorly, and cerebellum posteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes its location. The floor of the fourth ventricle is formed by the dorsal surface of the pons and medulla, while its roof is formed by the cerebellum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the cerebral hemispheres in the midline\u003C/strong\u003E describes the location of the third ventricle, which is a narrow, vertical cleft between the two thalami.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ewithin each cerebral hemisphere\u003C/strong\u003E description refers to the lateral ventricles (first and second ventricles), which are C-shaped cavities within each cerebral hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the third ventricle and cerebral aqueduct\u003C/strong\u003E is anatomically incorrect as the cerebral aqueduct (of Sylvius) connects the third and fourth ventricles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the thalamus and hypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this region contains part of the third ventricle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fourth ventricle is clinically significant as it contains the choroid plexus that produces cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and has three openings (two lateral apertures and one median aperture) through which CSF flows into the subarachnoid space. Obstruction of the fourth ventricle, as in this case, can lead to hydrocephalus and increased intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fourth ventricle is a diamond-shaped cavity located between the pons and medulla anteriorly, and the cerebellum posteriorly.","The fourth ventricle contains the choroid plexus and communicates with the central canal of the spinal cord and the subarachnoid space via distinct openings.","The lateral apertures (foramina of Luschka) and median aperture (foramen of Magendie) allow CSF to exit the fourth ventricle into the subarachnoid space."],"references":["Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Spierer R. The debated neuroanatomy of the fourth ventricle. J Anat. 2023 Oct;243(4):555-563. doi: 10.1111/joa.13885. Epub 2023 May 12. PMID: 37170923; PMCID: PMC10485575.","Roesch ZK, Tadi P. Neuroanatomy, Fourth Ventricle. [Updated 2023 Aug 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546577/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T11:52:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T11:53:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74658"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior